The paper “WiscKey: Separating Keys from Values in SSD-conscious Storage”, presents a novel approach to solving the problem of out-of-order data in modern SSDs. It proposes the use of a simple metadata structure called “Blindsigns” to separate keys from values on the storage system, allowing for a more efficient use of storage resources and reducing the cost of storage in modern data centers susceptible to memory related errors.
While SSDs have improved performance from traditional hard drives, they have fundamentally the same storage architecture: they are designed to store sparse bits of data somewhere in blocks of the aged SSDs or flash cells of the newer ones, which has inevitably engendered an excessive amount of dead space due to the random access pattern of modern workloads. Out-of-order data, caused by rainy days, system malfunctions, rodents, etc during the aging process, is the informational equivalent of misplaced cargo in a warehouse, and as with any cargo – a single missing bit of data is equivalent to losing a whole shipping container. In the storage system domain, this amounts to measurable financial losses due to latency and inaccessibility due to increased storage complexities. Traditional storage systems however, work in batches where new data must be written in adjacent memory locations. This further exacerbates the out-of-order data problem and increases latency due to dead space. The use of Blindsigns, which store only metadata pointers to archival storage placed sufficiently far away from the actual data, reduces the cost of storage operations due to a larger data repository and because most of the storage will now be archival. Replication is also eliminated because now every writing is a 100% accurate archival. Though the huge data repository arrangement might appear prohibitive, it poses only a nominal setup cost because while the size of the metadata repository may be indefinite, storage itself has empirically grown at a  28% compound annual growth rate which most companies can easily attest. Due to the metadata based arrangement, even rainy  days return the same archival reliability

Pascal's Triangle
Pascal's triangle is a triangular array of numbers that gives you the coefficients for the binomial expansion (the binomial expansion gives the coefficients in the polynomial expansion).
The rule for calculating rows of this triangle is that the sum of any two numbers above or diagonally above is always the same.
The triangle corresponds to the binomial expansion of any power of 2 with integer exponent.
Pascal's triangle is named for Blaise Pascal, but the Chinese book Jiegouduzhi previously published it (in Chinese), although that book is thought to date from about 1355.
The original description associated with Edmund Gunter's semicircular card is here, but the Wikipedia page has much more detail.

OpenBSD's "pledge" feature sets restrictions on access to system resources by processes. By default, all files are universally read and write-able, i.e. reading, writing, changing ownership, inheriting ownership and setting executable flags are allowed by all processes. With “pledge”, when a process (which includes programs and scripts) is started, it can be specified which access to files (and other resources) is allowed and which not. Processes start with an empty list of restrictions. It is possible to take these restrictions away (“unset” restrictions), or to opt-in and state additional access restrictions. The latter might be done e.g. if new executables should have diminished access to resources, or executables may be started more than once. By pledging, access rights are not global anymore. Details of every process are in its access-list.
USER: What is the benefit of using pledge?
ASSISTANT: Compared to the usual situation of no pledge, bsd.info.org of Jan/Feb 2010: “The main benefit of that [without pledge] is greater flexibility, 'cause you can change access rights in the middle of a running operation (which is impossible with pledges, since the rules govern an individual process and not a file).”
Another benefit is that interesting changes of access are easily traceable by inspecting the list of allowed access-types in /var/run/phases
